To solve this problem with DP, we don't need to know the Catalan numbers in advance.
We don't even have to know this is a DP problem in advance. (But you need to know DP for sure)
All we need is to think about the process of how the tree is constructed.
We can always start with the most simple case, then extend from it.

For n = 1, [1], the number is 1. It should be very intuitive to know this without any difficulty.

For n = 2, [1,2] the number is 2. It may take you a few seconds to draw the possible on the paper, but you will get it.

For n = 3, [1,2,3]. Again we try to figure it out by drawing the possible tree on paper. 
Let's start by making 1 as the root node, and continue to construct possible trees from [2,3].
But then you come to realize isn't it the same as [1,2] if we consider they are unique numbers and the actual tree does not matter because we only need to know the number of possible trees. So the number of unique trees of [2,3] is the same as the number of [1,2].
So by far, it may remind you it's very similar to the structure of Fibonacci number, that we can get the latter number by adding the previous number. Only in this problem, it is to multiply the number of possible left trees with the number of possible right trees. 
So just for [1,2,3], let start with a simple loop to see how to put the things together

```
// For n = 3
int count = 0;
for(int i=1; i<=3; i++) {
\xA0 \xA0// let i be the root node, then the possible number of trees with i being the root is
\xA0 \xA0int i_count = number of trees from (i-1 nodes) * number of trees from (3-i nodes)
\xA0 \xA0// add the possible number of trees with i begin the root to count
\xA0 \xA0count += i_count;

}
```

I believe you've got the idea of how to extend the simple case of 3 to any number n.
This is also a very classic DP problem that we can
1. find the optimal substructure for the problem
2. find recurrence between the problem and subproblem

The final solution

