If someone has already checked the solution, but still wonders **why there are TWO FOR loops**, while the formula only suggests ONE (at first glance)

$$\mathrm{G(n)} = \sum_{i=1}^n G(i - 1) * G(n - i) $$

Here is my attempt to explain.

Imagine we want to find G(3), it can be expressed as:
$$\mathrm{G(3)} = G(0) * G(2) + G(1) * G(1) + G(2) * G(0) $$

Now we don't know what is G(2), but we can calculate it like this:
$$\mathrm{G(2)} = G(0) * G(1) + G(1) * G(0) $$

We can clealy see that to calculate G(3), we need to know all previous G(2), G(1), and etc.

That's why it actually makes sense to start calculating from smaller number. eg: G(2), G(3), G(4) ..

We don't need to calculate G(0) and G(1) they are both 1.
1 node tree is 1 combination
0 node (empty tree) is 1 combination

So, now back to the original question.

```
public class Solution {
  public int numTrees(int n) {
    int[] G = new int[n + 1];
    G[0] = 1;
    G[1] = 1;

    for (int i = 2; i <= n; ++i) {
      for (int j = 1; j <= i; ++j) {
        G[i] += G[j - 1] * G[i - j];
      }
    }
    return G[n];
  }
}
```

So, we have 2 loops because to find `G(n)`, we first need to find all previous G(n-1), G(n-2) ... G(2).
So, we essentially first compute G(2) then G(3), G(4) and etc till G(n)

The outer loop `for (int i = 2; i <= n; ++i) {` is where we point which `G` we want to compute, so we start with G(2), then G(3) ... G(n)

The inner loop `for (int j = 1; j <= i; ++j) {` is actually the place where we compute the pointed G[i] using the formula:
$$\mathrm{G(i)} = \sum_{j=1}^n G(j - 1) * G(i - j) $$

In other words, due to recursive nature of the formula we have 2 for loops.

It took me a while to realise that.
Hope it will help someone else!

